1
00:01:20,730 --> 00:01:22,930
Why is this thing so heavy?

2
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:33,660
Oh, cool!

3
00:01:43,040 --> 00:01:44,550
How do I look?

4
00:01:45,940 --> 00:01:48,070
Was that hat in the trunk
you just brought up?

5
00:01:48,850 --> 00:01:50,630
What else is in there?

6
00:01:52,810 --> 00:01:54,500
These are.

7
00:01:55,160 --> 00:01:56,600
Oh...

8
00:01:57,160 --> 00:01:58,960
We may have brought up
the wrong trunk.

9
00:02:01,480 --> 00:02:03,040
Oh, yeah.

10
00:02:03,830 --> 00:02:05,740
Your mother wouldn't want
this up here.

11
00:02:06,340 --> 00:02:07,910
This is her...

12
00:02:08,110 --> 00:02:09,710
Her treasure chest.

13
00:02:13,340 --> 00:02:14,840
Can you play this?

14
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:17,050
No, I can't play 'em.

15
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:19,070
Your mother can, though.

16
00:02:19,230 --> 00:02:20,970
She loves
the bagpipes.

17
00:02:21,620 --> 00:02:24,240
I didn't think girls could
play the bagpipes.

18
00:02:24,360 --> 00:02:26,090
Your mother's not a girl.

19
00:02:26,980 --> 00:02:29,680
That is, your mother's
never really been a girl

20
00:02:29,760 --> 00:02:31,640
the way that
other girls...

21
00:02:32,350 --> 00:02:33,810
Are girls.

22
00:02:33,910 --> 00:02:36,850
Dad, I'd just leave that alone
If I were you.

23
00:02:38,610 --> 00:02:40,410
I wonder if it still works.

24
00:02:46,370 --> 00:02:47,880
What's this?

25
00:02:53,490 --> 00:02:55,160
It's a story...

26
00:02:56,250 --> 00:02:57,950
about your mom.

27
00:02:58,520 --> 00:03:00,450
Come on. I have an idea.

28
00:03:03,370 --> 00:03:04,810
Tell mom to tell you
the story

29
00:03:04,920 --> 00:03:06,800
just like she told it to me.Okay.

30
00:03:29,740 --> 00:03:32,450
Well, my, my, my, my...

31
00:03:33,790 --> 00:03:36,300
Hi.
Hi. How are you, so?

32
00:03:36,850 --> 00:03:39,630
And what brings you out
to the fields today, Lassie?

33
00:03:40,410 --> 00:03:42,110
I got something for ya.

34
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:48,350
Dad says there's a story in there.

35
00:03:50,070 --> 00:03:51,650
Oh, yes.

36
00:03:52,120 --> 00:03:53,970
I'm afraid I don't see it.

37
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:56,680
Well, that's because
there's a lot missing.

38
00:03:57,250 --> 00:03:59,220
You can see this is our farm,
though, right?

39
00:04:00,220 --> 00:04:04,420
Yeah, and these mountains
are those over there.

40
00:04:04,970 --> 00:04:08,370
Right.
And this is the old cemetery.

41
00:04:09,430 --> 00:04:11,310
And Ira is you, right?

42
00:04:11,610 --> 00:04:14,070
You don't like the name Iris,
do you?

43
00:04:14,300 --> 00:04:15,410
Nope.

44
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:17,440
Well, how old were you
In that picture?

45
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:20,320
I was 11 years old.

46
00:04:20,440 --> 00:04:23,050
I only had one more year left
of freedom.

47
00:04:24,250 --> 00:04:25,830
What do you mean?

48
00:04:26,270 --> 00:04:28,230
I mean that the next year

49
00:04:28,370 --> 00:04:29,810
I had to go out on the farm

50
00:04:29,910 --> 00:04:31,890
and work everyday
like my older sisters.

51
00:04:32,290 --> 00:04:33,800
What happened in this picture?

52
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:35,280
Who's Oscar?

53
00:04:35,700 --> 00:04:37,280
We have to go back
quite a'ways

54
00:04:37,380 --> 00:04:39,040
before we get to what
happened in this picture.

55
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:51,660
The enemy has advanced
far enough.

56
00:04:52,910 --> 00:04:54,450
Fire the cannons.

57
00:05:30,500 --> 00:05:32,990
Ira!

58
00:05:59,490 --> 00:06:01,180
We are waiting, Oscar.

59
00:06:02,420 --> 00:06:03,770
Sorry.

60
00:06:06,490 --> 00:06:08,570
We're not leaving
grandmother, Oscar.

61
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:13,440
She will be with us.

62
00:06:15,080 --> 00:06:16,730
She's with us now.

63
00:07:11,590 --> 00:07:14,120
If grandmother had been treated
the way people should be treated...

64
00:07:14,190 --> 00:07:17,360
when we work in the fields all our
life, she would still be alive today.

65
00:07:17,700 --> 00:07:20,490
- Please, don't say that.
- But it's true and it's how I feel.

66
00:07:20,650 --> 00:07:23,180
- Then, please don't say it around Oscar.
- Momma...

67
00:07:23,300 --> 00:07:26,260
The foreman said that the place
where we will be working this summer,

68
00:07:26,570 --> 00:07:28,050
It will be different.

69
00:07:28,120 --> 00:07:30,150
But that doesn't bring our
grandmother back, does it?

70
00:07:30,270 --> 00:07:32,050
But it can be good for us.

71
00:07:32,450 --> 00:07:34,340
And that will be good for Oscar.

72
00:07:35,970 --> 00:07:37,890
That is what I want now.

73
00:07:38,200 --> 00:07:41,720
Please, Marcus, help me to make
It good for him.

74
00:08:26,420 --> 00:08:29,470
Go out and tell the girls
to come in for dinner.

75
00:08:29,990 --> 00:08:31,200
Okay.

76
00:08:32,330 --> 00:08:34,120
No funny business, okay?

77
00:08:34,240 --> 00:08:37,060
Please. Just deliver the message.

78
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:48,840
If we have do the same thing again
for our vacation next year

79
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:51,080
As we do every year.

80
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:54,080
I'll just soon stay out here
and hoe beets.

81
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:55,840
Look how sick that I am!

82
00:08:55,940 --> 00:08:57,500
I'm not sick of it.

83
00:08:57,580 --> 00:08:59,080
What, you're not sick
of hoeing beets,

84
00:08:59,160 --> 00:09:00,680
or you're not sick of
the same vacation?

85
00:09:00,750 --> 00:09:03,270
- I'm not sick of the same vacation.
- I know.

86
00:09:03,630 --> 00:09:06,030
You like cotton candy.

87
00:09:06,590 --> 00:09:08,990
Little pigs. And birds.

88
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:11,030
And little bunny rabbits.

89
00:09:12,810 --> 00:09:15,140
And popcorn! And so does Ira.

90
00:09:15,730 --> 00:09:19,990
That's why we have to go do the same
old stupid thing we do every year.

91
00:09:20,140 --> 00:09:22,000
You just want to go see
the Beach Boys.

92
00:09:22,140 --> 00:09:23,430
Don't you?
Yeah.

93
00:09:23,550 --> 00:09:25,400
Well, then get on the train.

94
00:09:25,700 --> 00:09:27,560
If we're gonna talk mom and
dad into doing this,

95
00:09:27,630 --> 00:09:29,940
then we've all got to be
on board, including Ira.

96
00:09:30,130 --> 00:09:31,570
Well, that will never happen.

97
00:09:31,670 --> 00:09:34,770
She hates the beach boys.
She hates everything.

98
00:09:35,390 --> 00:09:37,810
Except her army men and baseball.

99
00:09:38,310 --> 00:09:39,800
She should have been born a boy.

100
00:09:39,910 --> 00:09:41,420
She is a boy.

101
00:09:41,510 --> 00:09:44,570
She doesn't do one thing or like
one single thing that girls like.

102
00:09:44,690 --> 00:09:46,170
She doesn't even like her name.

103
00:09:46,260 --> 00:09:48,420
Would you like your name if
is its Iris?

104
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:49,940
No.

105
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:52,070
But I wouldn't give myself
a man's name.

106
00:09:52,210 --> 00:09:55,510
It's not normal. Who's not skin
off your nose how she acts.

107
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:58,410
Wrong, I can't go anywhere,
do anything with my friends...

108
00:09:58,500 --> 00:10:00,090
without somebody asking me,

109
00:10:00,180 --> 00:10:01,950
"why is Ira like that?"

110
00:10:02,060 --> 00:10:04,400
She makes our whole family
look strange.

111
00:10:09,030 --> 00:10:10,770
No!

112
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:20,410
Ira, no!

113
00:10:20,610 --> 00:10:22,490
Dinner's ready!

114
00:10:27,690 --> 00:10:29,090
Ira!

115
00:10:35,730 --> 00:10:37,480
Get back here, Ira!

116
00:10:39,430 --> 00:10:41,270
I'm gonna kill you!

117
00:10:41,350 --> 00:10:43,090
You will die!

118
00:10:47,040 --> 00:10:50,220
Hey, dad, I heard about
this machine...

119
00:10:50,420 --> 00:10:53,110
It goes along the fields,
cuts out all the weeds

120
00:10:53,280 --> 00:10:54,710
And takes care of the beets...

121
00:10:55,020 --> 00:10:56,960
I never heard of anything
like that.

122
00:10:57,070 --> 00:10:58,670
They might be working on
something like that.

123
00:10:58,770 --> 00:11:00,110
What's it called?

124
00:11:00,190 --> 00:11:02,060
It's like a corilla...

125
00:11:02,180 --> 00:11:03,560
rilla...

126
00:11:05,060 --> 00:11:06,870
No, no, you mean a corrugator.

127
00:11:07,060 --> 00:11:08,820
See, that goes along and cuts
the furrows

128
00:11:08,930 --> 00:11:11,080
and then we run the water
down to irrigate.

129
00:11:11,860 --> 00:11:13,900
No, that's not what I'm
talking about.

130
00:11:14,380 --> 00:11:15,970
I can't remember.

131
00:11:16,980 --> 00:11:19,330
Well, I got the exact acreage...

132
00:11:19,370 --> 00:11:21,260
on the crop for this year.
From who?

133
00:11:21,450 --> 00:11:22,950
Jack, the surveyor.

134
00:11:23,090 --> 00:11:24,610
How much?No.

135
00:11:25,550 --> 00:11:27,370
Don't say it. I don't want
to know.

136
00:11:27,900 --> 00:11:30,260
It's a lot more than last year.
Let's just leave It at that.

137
00:11:30,950 --> 00:11:33,250
If we know it just makes
it worse

138
00:11:33,800 --> 00:11:35,790
You wannna to go to
college next year, right?

139
00:11:36,710 --> 00:11:39,540
This is part of the price we
have to pay to make that happen.

140
00:11:39,630 --> 00:11:41,810
Besides, you don't have to hoe
the whole crop by yourself.

141
00:11:42,050 --> 00:11:44,320
What do you mean?
I mean you're gonna have help.

142
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:47,520
From who?
From the little crop-hoeing
fairies, of course.

143
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:49,630
You are such a
dip, Iris.

144
00:11:49,760 --> 00:11:50,970
Thank you.

145
00:11:51,340 --> 00:11:52,740
No names, please.

146
00:11:52,820 --> 00:11:54,510
It's not a name.
It's what she is.

147
00:11:55,760 --> 00:11:57,370
Do you want to hear the rest
of this or not?

148
00:11:58,230 --> 00:11:59,570
Sorry.

149
00:12:00,340 --> 00:12:02,370
I went out to the labor camp,
maybe with the foreman,

150
00:12:02,520 --> 00:12:04,620
and gonna hire a couple of
mexican families to move in...

151
00:12:04,700 --> 00:12:06,530
and help us with the crop.

152
00:12:06,650 --> 00:12:08,600
That's what I was afraid you're
gonna say.

153
00:12:08,890 --> 00:12:10,090
Why?

154
00:12:10,220 --> 00:12:13,100
Because dad, you know all
that stuff that goes on

155
00:12:13,140 --> 00:12:14,690
when the mexicans
come in to work.

156
00:12:14,770 --> 00:12:16,060
It's a mess.

157
00:12:16,140 --> 00:12:18,030
Yes, but whose fault is that
most of the time, Jane?

158
00:12:18,130 --> 00:12:19,570
That's not the point, mom.

159
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:21,420
Then what is the point?
Ira...

160
00:12:21,960 --> 00:12:24,850
When the mexican workers
come in Summer

161
00:12:24,940 --> 00:12:26,300
It means trouble.

162
00:12:26,740 --> 00:12:28,060
It doesn't matter
who starts it.

163
00:12:28,230 --> 00:12:29,610
I'm sure it matters to them.

164
00:12:29,710 --> 00:12:31,180
I didn't mean like that.

165
00:12:31,540 --> 00:12:33,780
What I mean is when the fights
break out,

166
00:12:33,870 --> 00:12:36,110
What ends happening it's
always the same.

167
00:12:36,230 --> 00:12:38,560
Well, still the weeds are not
going to hoe themselves,

168
00:12:38,880 --> 00:12:40,330
and we can't do it all.

169
00:12:40,880 --> 00:12:43,140
Maybe we could hire some other
people to come the work.

170
00:12:43,550 --> 00:12:45,860
Like who? Your friends?
Sure.

171
00:12:46,120 --> 00:12:47,920
Right, Afton.
They'd come.

172
00:12:48,290 --> 00:12:50,030
Terry and chris?

173
00:12:50,380 --> 00:12:51,820
And Nancy?

174
00:12:52,150 --> 00:12:53,740
There's a picture for ya.

175
00:13:00,200 --> 00:13:01,830
I don't think you're being fair.

176
00:13:02,010 --> 00:13:04,990
Well, maybe not, but it's Ok
just this once,

177
00:13:05,060 --> 00:13:07,750
I'd like to hire somebody who
knows which end of the hoe to hold.

178
00:13:09,400 --> 00:13:10,940
When will the workers
be here?

179
00:13:11,080 --> 00:13:12,820
They should be here
ready to work monday.

180
00:13:14,750 --> 00:13:16,100
D-day.

181
00:13:16,610 --> 00:13:18,050
D-day?

182
00:13:18,510 --> 00:13:21,760
Invasion day, Aftonia.

183
00:13:25,580 --> 00:13:26,900
Dad?

184
00:13:27,590 --> 00:13:29,400
Can we go into town tomorrow?

185
00:13:30,190 --> 00:13:31,940
A little saturday day off.

186
00:13:33,380 --> 00:13:35,320
But, if you don't
work tomorrow,

187
00:13:35,520 --> 00:13:37,760
It doesn't go away. It just
gets moved to later.

188
00:13:38,040 --> 00:13:40,160
That's okay.
I believe in later.

189
00:14:31,540 --> 00:14:33,120
Who were they, mama?

190
00:14:33,760 --> 00:14:35,370
It doesn't matter.

191
00:14:43,810 --> 00:14:45,000
Where you going?

192
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:46,580
To the railroad tracks.

193
00:14:46,700 --> 00:14:48,320
If you're not back here when
the girls...

194
00:14:48,410 --> 00:14:50,240
leave for town no go without you.

195
00:14:50,330 --> 00:14:51,890
Down and pick me up there.

196
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:54,390
I'll tell them, but that doesn't
mean they'll do it.

197
00:15:06,760 --> 00:15:09,520
She's going for the record today,
ladies and gents.

198
00:15:10,200 --> 00:15:12,220
The last time we saw
this young lady,

199
00:15:12,410 --> 00:15:14,660
she tossed eight rocks
through the moving cars.

200
00:15:14,960 --> 00:15:16,670
Today she's gonna do ten.

201
00:15:17,350 --> 00:15:20,620
It seems impossible,
but she's vowed to do it.

202
00:15:26,480 --> 00:15:28,390
The first throw goes
right through

203
00:15:28,520 --> 00:15:30,160
and the crowd goes wild.

204
00:15:35,110 --> 00:15:36,450
Two.

205
00:15:37,030 --> 00:15:38,320
Three.

206
00:15:38,860 --> 00:15:39,750
Four.

207
00:15:39,820 --> 00:15:40,740
Five.

208
00:15:40,830 --> 00:15:41,990
Six.

209
00:15:43,530 --> 00:15:44,630
Seven.

210
00:15:49,560 --> 00:15:50,660
Eight.

211
00:15:50,710 --> 00:15:51,870
Nine.

212
00:16:04,950 --> 00:16:07,370
The poofy-headed sisters
are closing in.

213
00:16:08,020 --> 00:16:10,440
Only a few more seconds left
to break the record.

214
00:16:11,310 --> 00:16:12,740
Can she do it?

215
00:16:18,140 --> 00:16:20,220
Come on, let's go!

216
00:16:22,490 --> 00:16:23,890
She does it!

217
00:16:31,280 --> 00:16:32,660
Drop the bike!

218
00:16:32,740 --> 00:16:34,470
We'll pick it up later!

219
00:16:37,310 --> 00:16:39,380
She breaks the record with one
last throw.

220
00:16:39,530 --> 00:16:41,150
This kid is incredible.

221
00:16:41,250 --> 00:16:42,660
What a kid!

222
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:43,910
What a future!

223
00:16:43,990 --> 00:16:45,340
What a dip!

224
00:16:58,900 --> 00:17:00,470
Where you two been?

225
00:17:00,790 --> 00:17:02,500
Just down there.

226
00:17:03,250 --> 00:17:04,370
Seen Afton?

227
00:17:04,440 --> 00:17:05,680
Yeah, I saw her.

228
00:17:05,790 --> 00:17:07,910
She was talking with
Tav Jobarth.

229
00:17:08,980 --> 00:17:10,440
I've got to have a talk
with that girl

230
00:17:10,530 --> 00:17:12,040
about her taste in men.

231
00:17:12,210 --> 00:17:13,820
Teddy Allen was there, too.

232
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:15,430
See what I mean.

233
00:17:15,510 --> 00:17:17,140
Tav and Teddy, ugh!

234
00:17:32,540 --> 00:17:35,170
So, Jane, how ya doing?

235
00:17:35,940 --> 00:17:37,470
Fine, fine.

236
00:17:39,260 --> 00:17:40,660
Did you get a free bowl of soup

237
00:17:40,740 --> 00:17:42,200
with that haircut, Randy?

238
00:17:43,210 --> 00:17:45,240
You're not being
too friendly today, Jane.

239
00:17:46,030 --> 00:17:47,440
I'm being friendly.

240
00:17:47,530 --> 00:17:49,070
I like Randy's hair.

241
00:17:49,380 --> 00:17:50,890
You don't think I'm being
too unfriendly,

242
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:52,710
do you, Randy?
I don't know.

243
00:17:56,830 --> 00:17:59,000
Why don't you jump in with us?

244
00:17:59,130 --> 00:18:02,250
I'd love to, but I'm in
charge today.

245
00:18:02,500 --> 00:18:03,860
They'll be okay.

246
00:18:03,970 --> 00:18:06,050
Come on, two minutes.
Maybe some other time.

247
00:18:06,140 --> 00:18:07,820
You mean it?
Sure.

248
00:18:08,040 --> 00:18:10,200
Maybe sometime when
Blake's driving, maybe...

249
00:18:13,960 --> 00:18:15,370
Why does he gotta be driving?

250
00:18:15,450 --> 00:18:17,040
He doesn't even have a car.

251
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:18,720
I don't know.

252
00:18:20,420 --> 00:18:22,360
Well, would ya look at that.

253
00:18:28,190 --> 00:18:29,690
Summer's here.

254
00:18:34,940 --> 00:18:36,710
Hey, Jane, you know what we call
those trucks?

255
00:18:39,230 --> 00:18:40,960
Mexican airliners.

256
00:18:50,070 --> 00:18:51,870
They've had a long, hard trip.

257
00:18:53,760 --> 00:18:55,880
Come on, they don't need us to
stand here and stare at them.

258
00:19:05,970 --> 00:19:07,480
What happened? What is this?

259
00:19:07,850 --> 00:19:09,400
What did they threw?

260
00:19:09,930 --> 00:19:11,560
Marcus, where are you going?

261
00:19:28,720 --> 00:19:30,600
You got something to say
to me, bug?

262
00:19:35,890 --> 00:19:37,580
Did you drop this?

263
00:19:38,980 --> 00:19:40,730
Did you drop this?

264
00:19:40,840 --> 00:19:42,600
That's a nice beaner boy.

265
00:19:43,250 --> 00:19:44,610
